#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Research-grade and exploratory work on how agents might talk to each other — novel channels, encodings, or interaction modes. Sits alongside formal A2A protocols as a sandbox for ideas that haven't hardened into standards.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Audio-channel experiments where agents communicate via sound rather than text or structured messages.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Projects exploring voice or acoustic signaling as an inter-agent transport — agents emitting tones, speech, or compressed audio protocols to exchange information. A narrow experimental slot within agent-to-agent research.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Gibberlink]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Tools and services that agents invoke as capabilities, rather than frameworks for building agents themselves.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Top-level segment for utilities designed to be called by agents — communications, side-effect actions, and similar capability providers. Distinct from runtimes, frameworks, or harnesses; these are the things at the other end of a tool call.]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Messaging and communication tools that agents use to send, receive, or coordinate via human-style channels.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Services exposing email, chat, or mailbox-like primitives to agents as callable tools. Typically shipped as MCP servers or SDKs so an agent can send messages, read inboxes, and coordinate over standard comms channels.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* MCP Agent Mail]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[General agent projects and agent subtypes that do not fit more specific segments.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Xata Agent]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Long-running autonomous agents that pursue goals with minimal human supervision.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Agents designed to operate open-endedly against a goal, planning and executing over extended horizons without turn-by-turn prompting. Distinct from chat assistants, harnesses, or task-specific agents — the defining trait is self-directed operation.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Autonomous agents that execute trading strategies in financial or crypto markets.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Self-directed agents that monitor markets, form views, and place trades without per-decision human approval. Typically shipped as runnable services or bots wired into exchange APIs.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* AI-Trader]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents (or platforms) whose purpose is to spawn and configure other autonomous agents.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Meta-level tools where the output is a new agent — skill bundles, agent factories, or systems that compose runnable agents from specs. Sits above individual agents in the stack as a creation layer.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* BankrBot Skills]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Self-hostable backend platforms for building, deploying, and serving LLM-powered agents and apps.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Full-stack platforms — usually open source, often with a UI — that provide workflow, RAG, tool, and model plumbing behind an API. Contrast with libraries (frameworks) or managed SaaS: these are deployable services developers run to host agent applications.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Dify]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Command-line agents and developer toolkits for running agents from the terminal.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[CLI-first agent surfaces — coding agents, general assistants, and SDK-style toolkits invoked from a shell. Sits at the developer-interface layer of the stack, distinct from web frontends or backend services.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Vendor-published official CLI agents shipped by model providers as first-party terminal tools.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Official command-line agents released by the companies that train or host the underlying models. Distinguished from community CLIs by being the canonical vendor distribution.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Qwen Code]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents and frameworks that operate a computer the way a human would (mouse, keyboard, screen).]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* open-computer-use]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Desktop graphical interfaces for interacting with agents.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Hello Halo]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Software-engineering agents that read, write, and modify code to complete development tasks.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Agents purpose-built for coding work — repo navigation, patch generation, test running, PR authoring. Distinct from general assistants by their tight integration with code, shells, and dev-loop feedback.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* OpenHands]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents specialised for a particular vertical or professional domain rather than general use.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Parent slot for agents whose value comes from domain expertise — biotech, legal, finance, and similar. Children split by the specific field; membership implies the agent is meaningfully tailored to that domain's data, tools, or workflows.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents specialised for biotech, bioinformatics, and life-sciences research workflows.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Agents built to assist with biology and biotech tasks such as literature mining, sequence analysis, lab protocol generation, and experiment planning. They typically wrap domain tools and datasets behind an LLM-driven interface.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Biomni]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[General-purpose frameworks for building agents and agentic applications.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Open-source general-purpose agent frameworks under permissive or copyleft licences.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Freely available frameworks for building agents and agentic applications, distinguished from proprietary or hosted alternatives by their open codebases. They provide core loops, tool integration, and orchestration primitives developers can run and modify locally.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Hermes Agent]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[User-facing interfaces — web, desktop, mobile, terminal — for interacting with agents.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* OpenClaw Mission Control]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Test harnesses and runner frameworks that host and exercise agents.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Command-line harnesses that host and run agents in a terminal environment.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[CLI-shaped runners that execute agents interactively or non-interactively from the shell. They sit at the execution layer of the stack, wrapping a model plus tools behind a terminal UX, and split into vendor-built and third-party implementations.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 36pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Third-party CLI harnesses not built by the underlying model vendor.]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Community or independent CLI runners that host agents against one or more model providers. They offer alternative terminal UXs and feature sets distinct from vendor-shipped CLIs.]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Crush]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 36pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Vendor-shipped CLI harnesses built by the model provider themselves.]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Official terminal agent runners published by the company behind the underlying model, such as Google's Gemini CLI or Anthropic's Claude Code. They provide a first-party execution surface tightly coupled to the vendor's models and APIs.]]
#block(inset: (left: 44pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Gemini CLI]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Memory systems for agents — short-term, long-term, episodic, file-backed, graph-backed.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Memory systems that construct and maintain knowledge graphs from agent interactions.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Tools that extract entities and relations from conversations, documents, or events and persist them as a graph used for long-term agent memory. They sit between raw logs and retrieval, turning unstructured history into structured, queryable memory.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Graphiti]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents built for a specific operational purpose that does not map to a domain vertical.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[A slot for agents defined by the task they perform (e.g. penetration testing, QA, triage) rather than by industry or framework. Distinguished from Domain Specific, which groups by vertical, and from Frameworks, which group by building blocks.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* INKOS]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents that autonomously perform offensive security and penetration testing tasks.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Security-focused agents that enumerate, probe, and exploit systems in a controlled way, chaining recon and exploitation tools under LLM direction. They sit alongside traditional pentesting frameworks as an autonomous execution layer.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Pentagi]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Tools that assemble and configure multi-agent teams from roles or task descriptions.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Systems whose job is to decide which agents to spawn, with what roles, tools, and prompts, to tackle a given objective. They sit upstream of multi-agent runtimes, producing the team that another layer then executes.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Squad]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Preconfigured multi-agent teams targeting a specific workflow or domain.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Ready-made collections of cooperating agents wired together for a particular use case, such as data science or content production. Distinct from Team Formation (which builds teams) and from Frameworks (which provide the primitives).]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* AI Data Science Team]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Agents whose primary modality is visual perception of images or video.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Agents built around vision models that analyse, describe, or act on image and video inputs, often as part of a broader multimodal loop. They sit alongside text and computer-use agents as a distinct perceptual slot in the stack.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Vision Agents]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Browsers built or adapted specifically for AI agent use, including headless variants optimised for programmatic navigation.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* BrowserOS]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Headless browsers optimised for programmatic navigation by AI agents.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Browser engines without a visible UI, tuned for automated page loading, DOM access, and scraping under agent control. They sit below agent frameworks as the execution substrate for web interaction, competing with general-purpose headless tools repurposed for AI use.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Lightpanda Browser, Steel Browser]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Human labeling, RLHF, and feedback-collection platforms for agent training data.]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[General-purpose automation tools and frameworks, including GUI-driven and script-driven flows.]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Open-source automation platforms and frameworks for building agentic workflows.]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Self-hostable automation tools that power agent-driven workflows, spanning GUI-first builders and script-based engines. Sits alongside proprietary SaaS automation platforms but distinguished by open licensing and self-hosting.]]
#block(above: 0.6em, below: 0.2em, inset: (left: 24pt))[#text(size: 10.5pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Open-source visual/no-code builders for composing automation and agent workflows.]]
#block(inset: (left: 32pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Drag-and-drop canvas tools where flows, triggers and agent steps are wired visually rather than in code. Typically self-hosted, targeting makers who want n8n/Zapier-style UX with open licensing.]]
