#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Simulations focused specifically on geopolitical scenarios and dynamics.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Snowglobe, WargamesAI]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Guardrails and pre-execution safety checks that gate what running agents can do.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Shellfirm]]
#block(above: 1.2em, below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 14pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#1a365d"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Execution-layer scaffolding that wraps agents for real runs — sub-agent dispatch, long-horizon coherence, checkpointing, platform-specific runtimes.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.3em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2d3748"))[Harnesses sit between frameworks (which define agent shape) and runtimes (which provide the sandbox). They're the execution-layer utilities that make long-running, multi-step agent runs actually work in practice: spawning isolated sub-agent contexts, resuming from checkpoints, recovering from tool failures, keeping the main thread coherent over time, and adapting to the host platform.]]
#block(inset: (left: 8pt), below: 0.4em)[#text(size: 8.5pt, fill: rgb("#2f855a"))[*Examples:* Hive, oh-my-openagent]]
#block(above: 0.8em, below: 0.3em, inset: (left: 12pt))[#text(size: 12pt, weight: "bold", fill: rgb("#2b6cb0"))[]]
#block(inset: (left: 20pt), below: 0.2em)[#text(size: 9pt, style: "italic", fill: rgb("#4a5568"))[Save and restore agent execution state across interruptions, crashes, or session boundaries.]]
